{"parse":{"title":"friend","pageid":5137,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Friend}}\n==English==\n{{wp|+ship}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|frind||pronunciation spelling}}\n* {{alt|en|freind||misspelling}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|:inh|enm:frend|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|freend}}, {{m|enm|frend}}, {{m|enm|frende}}, {{m|enm|freynde}}, {{m|enm|friend}}, {{m|enm|frind}}, {{m|enm|frond}}, {{m|enm|frund}}, {{m|enm|vrend}}, {{m|enm|vryend}}, from {{inh|en|ang|frēond}}, {{m|ang|frīond|t=friend|lit=loving [one], lover}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*friund}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*frijōndz|t=friend, loved one}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*preyH-|t=to please; to love}}, roughly equivalent to {{suffix|enm|free|and|alt2=nd|nocat=1}}. See also [[Friday]].\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|freend|t=friend}}, {{cog|yol|friend}}, {{m|yol|vriene|t=friend}}, {{cog|frr|frinj}}, {{m|frr|frün|t=friend}}, {{cog|stq|Fjund}}, {{m|stq|Früünd|t=friend}}, {{cog|fy|freon}}, {{m|fy|freondinne|t=friend}}, {{cog|cim|bròint}}, {{m|cim|vròint|t=friend}}, {{cog|nl|vriend|t=friend}}, {{cog|de|Freund|t=friend}}, {{cog|nds-de|Fründ|t=friend, relative}}, {{cog|li|vröndj|t=friend}}, {{cog|lb|Frënd|t=friend}}, {{cog|wym|fraeind}}, {{m|wym|frajnd|t=friend}}, {{cog|yi|פֿרײַנד|t=friend}}, {{cog|da|frænde|t=kinsman}}, {{cog|fo,is|frændi|t=kinsman}}, {{cog|nb,nn|frende|t=relative}}, {{cog|sv|frände|t=kinsman, relative}}, {{cog|got|𐍆𐍂𐌹𐌾𐍉𐌽𐌳𐍃|t=friend}}; also {{cog|cy|rhydd|t=free}}, {{cog|la|proprius|t=own, proper}}, {{cog|be|пры́яцель|t=friend}}, {{cog|bg|прия́тел|t=male friend}}, {{cog|cs|přítel|t=friend; supporter; lover}}, {{cog|mk|при́јател|t=friend, mate, pal}}, {{cog|pl|przyjaciel}}, {{m|pl|przyjáciel|t=friend; lover}}, {{cog|ru|прия́тель|t=friend; buddy, mate, pal}}, {{cog|sh|при̏јатељ}}, {{m|sh|prȉjatelj|t=friend}}, {{cog|sk|priateľ|t=friend; supporter}}, {{cog|sl|prijatelj|t=friend; companion; chum}}, {{cog|uk|при́ятель|t=friend; buddy, pal}}, {{cog|ae|𐬟𐬭𐬌𐬌𐬀|t=good, pleasant}}, {{cog|fa|فری|tr=fari|t=beloved, dear; pleasing}}, {{cog|sa|प्रिय|t=beloved; own, wonted}}. More at {{m|en|free}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|frĕnd|a=RP,GA}}, {{IPA|en|/fɹɛnd/|[fɹ̥ɛnd]|[fɹ̥ɛnd̥]}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-friend.ogg|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-friend.ogg|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/frɪnd/|a=dialectal,especially with <<pin-pen>>|ref={{R:Bingham IP|75}}}}<!--not just pin-pen-->\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛnd|s=1}}\n* {{hyph|en|friend}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A person, typically someone other than a [[family]] [[member]], [[spouse]] or [[lover]], whose company one enjoys and towards whom one feels [[affection]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1816|author=w:Jane Austen|title=[[s:Emma (Austen)/Volume 3/Chapter 13|Emma]]|passage=\"[…]if you have any wish to speak openly to me as a '''friend''', or to ask my opinion of any thing that you may have in contemplation—as a '''friend''', indeed, you may command me.—I will hear whatever you like. I will tell you exactly what I think.\" \"As a '''friend'''!\"—repeated Mr. Knightley.—\"Emma, that I fear is a word—No, I have no wish—[…]”}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1841|author=w:Ralph Waldo Emerson|chapter=Friendship|title={{w|Essays: First Series|Essays}}|volume=I\n|passage=The only reward of virtue is virtue; the only way to have a '''friend''' is to be one.}}\n#* '''1917''', Richard M. Gummere translating {{w|Seneca the Younger|Seneca}} as ''{{w|Epistulae Morales ad Lucilium|Ad Lucilium Epistulae Morales}}'', Loeb Classical Library, Vol. I, [[:s:Moral letters to Lucilius/Letter 3|No. 3]]:\n#*: ...if you consider any man a '''friend''' whom you do not trust as you trust yourself, you are mightily mistaken and you do not sufficiently understand what true [[friendship]] means.\n#* '''1923''', William Armistead Falconer translating {{w|Cicero}} as ''[https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html De Amicitia]'', Loeb Classical Library, Vol. XX, p. 34:\n#*: ...he who looks upon a true '''friend''', looks, as it were, upon a sort of image of himself. Wherefore '''friends''', though absent, are at hand; though in need, yet abound; though weak, are strong; and&mdash;harder saying still&mdash;though dead, are yet alive; so great is the esteem on the part of their '''friends''', the tender recollection and the deep longing that still attends them.\n#* '''1927 Mar. 31''', {{w|Ernest Hemingway}}, [https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=SgKeQfmimJEC&pg=PA248 letter] to {{w|F. Scott Fitzgerald}}:\n#*: ...you are my devoted '''friend''' too. You do more and work harder and oh shit I'd get [[maudlin]] about how damned [[swell]] you are. My god I'd like to see you... You're a hell of a good guy.\n#* '''1933 Dec. 12''', {{w|Walter Winchell}}, \"On Broadway\", ''Scranton Republican'', p. 5:\n#*: Definition of a '''friend''': One who walks in&mdash;when the rest of the world walks out.\n#: {{ux|en|John and I have been '''friends''' ever since we were roommates at college.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Trust is important between '''friends'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I used to find it hard to make '''friends''' when I was shy.}}\n#: {{ux|en|We became '''friends''' in the war and remain '''friends''' to this day.}}\n#: {{ux|en|We were '''friends''' with some girls from the other school and stayed '''friends''' with them.}}\n# An [[associate]] who provides [[assistance]]; patron, mentor.\n#* {{quote-text|en|format=letter|year=1779|author={{w|Benjamin Franklin}}|title=[[s:The Whistle (Franklin, 1779)|The Whistle]]|text=When I was a child of seven years old, my '''friends''', on a holiday, filled my little pocket with halfpence.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1813|author={{w|Jane Austen}}|title=[[s:Pride and Prejudice (1813)/Volume 2/Chapter 12|Pride and Prejudice]]|text= The vicious propensities—the want of principle which he was careful to guard from the knowledge of his best '''friend''', could not escape the observation of a young man of nearly the same age with himself, and who had opportunities of seeing him in unguarded moments, which Mr. Darcy could not have.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|format=poem|year=1907|author={{w|Hilaire Belloc}}|title=[[s:Cautionary Tales for Children/Jim|Jim]]|text= There was a Boy whose name was Jim; His '''Friends''' were very good to him. They gave him Tea, and Cakes, and Jam, And slices of delicious Ham, And Chocolate with pink inside, And little Tricycles to ride, And read him Stories through and through, And even took him to the Zoo—}}\n#: {{ux|en|The Automobile Association is every motorist's '''friend'''.&nbsp;&nbsp; The police is every law-abiding citizen's '''friend'''.}}\n# A person with whom one is [[vaguely]] or [[indirectly]] [[acquainted]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-21|author=w:Oliver Burkeman\n|volume=189|issue=2|page=27|magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly\n|title=[http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/may/10/conscious-computing-twitter-facebook-google The tao of tech]\n|passage=The dirty secret of the internet is that all this distraction and interruption is immensely profitable. Web companies like to boast about [&hellip;], or offering services that let you \"stay up to date with what your '''friends''' are doing\",{{...}}and so on. But the real way to build a successful online business is to be better than your rivals at undermining people's control of their own attention.}}\n#: {{coi|en|a '''friend''' of a '''friend'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|I added him as a '''friend''' on Facebook, but I hardly know him.}}\n# A person who backs or supports something.\n#: {{ux|en|I’m not a '''friend''' of cheap wine.}}\n# {{lb|en|informal}} An object or idea that can be used for good.\n#: {{ux|en|Fruit is your '''friend'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial|ironic|used only in the [[vocative]]}} {{n-g|Used as a form of [[address]] when [[warn]]ing someone.}}\n#: {{ux|en|You’d better watch it, '''friend'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|object-oriented programming}} A [[function]] or [[class]] granted special access to the [[private]] and [[protected]] [[member]]s of another class.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1991|author=Tom Swan|title=Learning C++|passage=But don't take the following sections as an endorsement of '''friends'''. Top C++ programmers avoid using '''friends''' unless absolutely necessary.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2001|author=Stephen Prata|title=C++ primer plus|passage=In that case, the function needn't (and shouldn't) be a '''friend'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=D S Malik|title=C++ Programming: From Problem Analysis to Program Design|passage=To make a function be a '''friend''' to a class, the reserved word <code>friend</code> precedes the function prototype{{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|climbing}} A [[spring-loaded camming device]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1995|title=Rock Climbing Basics\n|passage=Since they were introduced in the 1970s, '''friends''' have revolutionized climbing, making protection possible in previously impossible places {{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|euphemistic}} A [[lover]]; a [[boyfriend]] or [[girlfriend]].\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Love's Labour's Lost|5|2|passage=Nor to the motion of a schoolboy's tongue ; Nor never come in visard to my '''friend'''}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1813|author=Samuel Foote|title=The Commissary, Etc.|page=17\n|passage=Time has been, when a gentleman wanted a '''friend''', I could supply him with choice in an hour; but the market is spoiled, and a body might as soon produce a hare or a partridge {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1975|author=w:Janis Ian|title=In the Winter\n|passage=I met your '''friend'''. She's very nice, what can I say?}}\n# {{lb|en|Scotland|obsolete}} A [[relative]], a [[relation]] by blood or marriage.\n#: '''''Friends''' agree best at a distance.''<!--James Kelly, ''A Complete Collection of Scottish Proverbs'' (1721): \"By friends here is meant relations.\"-->\n#: ''Make '''friends''' of framet folk.''<!--James Kelly, ''A Complete Collection of Scottish Proverbs'' (1721): \"Spoken to dissuade people from marrying their near kinswomen.\"-->\n#* '''1895''', Crockett, ''Bog-Myrtle'', 232:\n#*: He was not a drop's blood to me, though him and my wife were far-out '''friends'''.\n# {{lb|en|in the plural|usually preceded by \"and\"}} {{ng|Used to refer collectively to a group of associated individuals, especially those comprising a cast, company, or crew}}\n#: {{syn|en|company|alt1=and company|et al.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Meanwhile on ''The View'', Whoopi Goldberg and '''friends''' continue to spout their takes on the hot topics of the day.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2020|author=Beth Van Schaack|title=Imagining Justice for Syria|isbn=9780190055967|page=98\n|text=Russia and '''friends''' continued to criticize the work of the JIM, focusing in particular on the methodology employed and the decision of the experts not to go to certain on-site visits for security reasons{{nb...}}}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* ''friends'' is found as an invariable plural in the phrases ''make friends with'' and ''be friends with'': ''I am '''friends''' with her''; ''He made '''friends''' with his co-worker.''\n* We usually ''[[make]] a friend'', or ''make friends with'' someone. See '''[[:Appendix:Collocations of do, have, make, and take]]'''\n* In older texts and certain dialects, the prepositional phrase '''to friend''' means \"as a friend or an ally\", for exampleː \"[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Faerie_Queene/Book_I/Canto_I with God to frend] (Spenser)\". The antonym to the phrase '''to friend''' is '''to [[fiend]]'''.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|person one likes to socialize with}} {{see thesaurus|en|friend}}\n* {{sense|sympathizer, helper}} {{l|en|ally}}\n* {{sense|boyfriend or girlfriend}} {{see thesaurus|en|lover}}\n* {{sense|person with whom you are acquainted}} {{l|en|acquaintance}}, {{l|en|contact}}\n* {{sense|person who backs something}} {{l|en|admirer}}, {{l|en|booster}}, {{l|en|champion}}, {{l|en|protagonist}}, {{l|en|supporter}}\n* {{sense|form of address used in warning someone}} {{l|en|buster}}, {{l|en|mate}} {{qualifier|British}}, [[pal]], [[buddy]], [[sonny]]\n\n====Antonyms====\n* {{antsense|person whose company one enjoys}} {{see thesaurus|en|enemy}}\n* {{antsense|person with whom you are acquainted}} {{l|en|stranger}}\n* {{antsense|person who provides assistance}} {{l|en|enemy}}, {{l|en|foe}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en\n|affriended\n|a friend in need is a friend indeed\n|all-weather friend\n|asking for a friend\n|backfriend,back-friend\n|befriend\n|best friend\n|best friend forever|climber's friend\n|big friend\n|bosom friend\n|boy-friend,boy friend,boyfriend\n|chick-friend,chick friend\n|childhood friend|my friend\n|circle of friends\n|close friend\n|cyberfriend\n|diamonds are a girl's best friend\n|Dorothy's friend\n|dumb friend\n|e-friend\n|enbyfriend\n|enemies-to-friends-to-lovers\n|ex-friend\n|fair-weather friend,fair weather friend,fairweather friend\n|false friend\n|family friend\n|fast friend\n|feathered friend\n|fine-feathered friend\n|flu friend\n|four-legged friend\n|framily\n|fremesis\n|frenemy\n|friend at court\n|friendboy\n|friend boy\n|friendess\n|friendful\n|friendgirl\n|friend girl\n|friend group\n|friendhood\n|friend-in-law\n|friendish\n|friendiversary\n|friendless\n|friendlike\n|friendling\n|friendlist\n|friendly\n|friendmaking\n|friendo\n|friend of a friend\n|friend of Bill\n|friend of Bill's\n|friend of Bill W.\n|friend of Bluey\n|friend of court\n|friend of Dorothy\n|friend of mine\n|friend of ours\n|friend of the court|friend price\n|friendom\n|friend request\n|Friends\n|Friendsgiving\n|friend-shaped\n|friendship\n|friendshiply\n|friendshoring\n|friendsies\n|friends in higher places\n|friends in high places\n|friends in low places\n|friends list\n|Friendsmas\n|friendsome\n|Friendster\n|friends-to-lovers\n|friend-to-friend\n|friend with benefits\n|friendworthy\n|friendy\n|friend zone\n|friend-zone\n|friend zonee\n|friend-zonee\n|fuckfriend\n|furriend\n|galfriend\n|girl friend\n|girl-friend\n|girlfriend\n|glue friend\n|good friend\n|Google is your friend\n|grandfriend\n|guy friend\n|guy-friend\n|half-friend\n|hi-bye friend\n|identification friend or foe\n|imaginary friend\n|just friends\n|lady friend\n|litigation friend\n|little friend\n|make friends\n|manfriend\n|man's best friend\n|McKenzie friend\n|merfriend\n|misfriend\n|m'learned friends\n|monthly friend\n|more than friends\n|motorman's friend\n|mouth-friend\n|mutual friend\n|my enemy's enemy is my friend\n|my learned friend\n|nepo friend\n|nepotism friend\n|newfriend\n|next friend\n|Nigel no friends\n|Nigel No Friends\n|Nigel no-friends\n|nonfriend\n|non-friend\n|old friend\n|old man's friend\n|out-friend\n|outfriend\n|partial false friend\n|penfriend\n|pen-friend\n|pen friend\n|playfriend\n|plumber's friend\n|prisoner's friend\n|Religious Society of Friends\n|say hello to my little friend\n|schoolfriend\n|semifriend\n|short accounts make long friends\n|short reckonings make long friends\n|Society of Friends\n|special friend\n|squirrel friend\n|stepfriend\n|superfriend\n|the enemy of my enemy is my friend\n|the enemy of your enemy is your friend\n|theyfriend\n|true friend\n|unfriend\n|un-friend\n|waiter's friend\n|what are friends for\n|wife's best friend\n|Wigner's friend\n|with friends like these who needs enemies\n|womanfriend\n|frienvy\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|jam|fren}}\n* {{desc|kri|frɛn}}\n* {{desc|yue|-|bor=1}} {{l|zh|friend|tr=fen{{sup|1}}}}\n* {{desc|fi|frendi|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sh|-|bor=1}}\n** {{desc|sh|frȅnd|sclang=1}}\n** {{desc|sh|фре̏нд|sclang=1}}\n* {{desc|es|friend|bor=1}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To act as a friend to, to [[befriend]]; to be friendly to, to help.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1596|author=Edmund Spenser|title=The Faerie Queene|section=IV.ii\n|passage=Lo sluggish Knight the victors happie pray: / So fortune '''friends''' the bold [...].}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1896|author=w:Alfred Edward Housman|title=w:A Shropshire Lad|section=LXII\n|passage=’Tis true, the stuff I bring for sale<br>Is not so brisk a brew as ale:<br>Out of a stem that scored the hand<br>I wrung it in a weary land.<br>But take it: if the smack is sour,<br>The better for the embittered hour;<br>It should do good to heart and head<br>When your soul is in my soul’s stead;<br>And I will '''friend''' you, if I may,<br>In the dark and cloudy day.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To add (a person) to a [[list]] of friends on a [[social networking]] site; to officially designate (someone) as a friend.\n#: {{ant|en|defriend|unfriend}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Kevin Farnham; Dale G. Farnham|title=Myspace Safety: 51 Tips for Teens And Parents|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=t0ykIJl4oAEC&pg=PA69&dq=%22friend+someone%22&sig=ACfU3U07tfwMQUkPDjT1RSxhAX6wgSJG6w|page=69|publisher=How-To Primers|isbn=0977883353\n|passage=One of the most used features of MySpace is the practice that is nicknamed \"friending.\" If you \"'''friend'''\" someone, then that person is added to your MySpace friends list, and you are added to their friends list.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2007|author=David Fono; Kate Raynes-Goldie|chapter=Hyperfriendship and Beyond: Friends and Social Norms on LiveJournal|editor=Mia Consalvo; Caroline Haythornthwaite|title=Internet Research Annual: Selected Papers from the Association of Internet Researchers Conference 2005|volume=4|series=Digital Formations|seriesvolume=33|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:[[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]]|issn=1526-3169|isbn=9780820478579|page=99|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=I0sKFgXY9D4C&pg=PA99&dq=friend|passage=The two distributions which exhibited this property were in response to the statements, “I am careful about who I '''friend''',” and, “If someone friends me, I will '''friend''' them.” (Figure 3).}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|author=w:Tommy Orange|chapter=Edwin Black|title=w:[[There There (novel)|There There]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Vintage Books|isbn=9780525436140|page=69|passage=I use Native, that’s what other Native people on Facebook use. I have 660 friends. Tons of Native friends in my feed. Most of my friends, though, are people  I don’t know, who’d happily '''friended''' me upon request.}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-see|befriend}}\n\n{{trans-top|to act as the friend of}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t|af|bevriend wees}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|сябрава́ць}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|bevriend zijn met}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|auttaa}}, {{t+|fi|avittaa}}\n* German: {{t+|de|anfreunden|alt=sich anfreunden}}\n* Persian: {{t|fa|دوستی کردن|tr=dusti kardan}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|przyjaźnić się}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|favorecer}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|дружи́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|подружи́ться|pf}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|favorecer}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|hjälpa}}, {{t+|sv|gynna}}, {{t+|sv|stödja}}\n* Tatar: {{t|tt|дуслашырга}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|dostey kerden}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to add as a friend}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t|af|vriende raak}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|сприятеля́вам се}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|加|tr=jiā}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|sõbrunema}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[lisätä]] [[kaveri]]ksi}}\n* French: {{t|fr|se lier d'amitié|alt=se lier d'amitié (avec)}}\n* Hungarian: {{t|hu|ismerősnek jelöl}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|dodać do znajomych}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|amigar}}, {{t|pt|[[marcar]] [[como]] [[amigo]]}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|зафре́ндить|pf|tr=zafrɛńditʹ}} {{qualifier|Internet}}, {{t|ru|[[доба́вить]] в [[друзья́]]}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|пријатељевати|alt=пријатељевати се}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|prijateljevati|alt=prijateljevati se}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|spriateliť sa|n}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|amistar}}, {{t|es|hacer amigos}}, {{t+|es|amigar}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|kaibiganin}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|зафре́ндити}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|embaz kerden}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=definr|Friden|finder|frined|redfin|refin'd|refind}}\n\n{{cln|en|endearing terms|terms of address}}\n{{C|en|People|Friendship}}\n\n==Chinese==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|zh|fd|frd}}\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|yue|en|friend}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{zh-pron\n|c=fen1\n|cat=n,a\n}}\n* {{a|zh|Cantonese (alternative)}}: {{IPA|yue|/fɹɛːn⁵⁵/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|zh|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Cantonese}} {{l|en|friend}} {{zh-mw|c:個}}\n#: {{zh-x|佢 係 我 個 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 嚟 㗎。|He's my '''friend'''.|C}}\n#* {{zh-x|我 個 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 話：「唔 會 衰 嘅，邊 有 咁 容易 吖，世界 咁 多 人 死 又 唔 見 你 去 死。」|My '''friend''' said, \"It's not gonna go wrong. It's not that easy [to go wrong]. There are so many people in the world, and I don't see you dying.\"|C|ref='''2008''', {{lang|zh|李紫媚}} (Jessica Li), {{lang|zh|《盜與罪：青少年犯罪預防理論與對策》}} (''Theft and delinquency: juvenile crime prevention theories and practice''), [https://books.google.com/books?id=VRQfAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA180 page 180]}}\n#* {{zh-x|喂，乜 你 班 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 咁{gam2} 踢波 嘅{ge2}，係咪{mai6} 有 啲 唔 對路？|Hey, how come your '''friends''' play soccer like this. Is there some problem?|C|ref='''2015''', Playboy {{lang|zh|文}} (pseudonym), {{lang|zh|《港股策略王》}}, issue 18, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ri7ACAAAQBAJ&pg=PA69 page 69]}}\n#* {{zh-x|我 個 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 叫 我 去 佢 屋企{kei2} 坐 吓{haa5}，但 又 唔 話 我 知 佢 女友 喺度，搞到 我 變 咗 做 電燈膽。|When my '''friend''' invited me to hang out at his house but he didn't tell me that his girlfriend would be there too, he made me a third wheel.|C|ref='''2016''', {{lang|zh|董德偉}}, {{lang|zh|《英語講呢D》}}, [https://books.google.ca/books?id=ERvcDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA101 page 101]}}\n# {{lb|zh|Cantonese|always with the classifier}} [[the likes of]]; something [[similar]] to {{zh-mw|c:啲}}\n#* {{quote-journal|zh|url=https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E6%B8%AF%E8%81%9E/article/20210918/s00002/1631902547882/|date=2021-09-18|work=w:Ming Pao}}\n#*: {{zh-x|警方 昨 向 黃 發信，指 漫畫 提到 假新聞 是 從「少{siu3}年警訊 啲 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 傳出 嚟 㗎」，對 漫畫 的 無理 指控 表達 強{koeng4}烈 不滿 和 關注，要{jiu1}求 澄清。|The police sent a letter to Wong yesterday, claiming the comic had mentioned that the fake news was “spread out from '''the likes of''' {{w|yue:少年警訊|Junior Police Call}}”. They expressed strong dissatisfaction and attention towards the unreasonable accusation by the comic, requesting a clarification.|C}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{s|friend}}\n{{zh-dial|朋友}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|zh|adjective}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Cantonese}} in a [[close]] or [[friendly]] [[relationship]]\n#: {{zh-x|我哋 好 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 㗎。|We are really '''close'''.|C}}\n#* {{quote-song|zh|year=1985|artist=lw:zh:許冠傑|title=zh:日本娃娃}}\n#*: {{zh-q|實行{hang4} 用 㗎{gaa4}文{man4-2} 跟 佢 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 吓|Used a bit of Japanese to try and make friends with her|C}}\n#* {{zh-x|「因為 你哋 五 個 好似 好 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 好 開心 噉 喎{wo3}。」|“It's because you five seem so '''close''' and happy.”|C|ref='''2011''', TVB-J2, {{lw|zh|K-ON！！輕音少女}} (''{{w|K-On!!}}''), season 2, episode 1}}\n#* {{zh-x|我 叫 奧 古，和 她 識 了 很多 年，算 係 好 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 下{haa5}。|My name is ''Ou Gu''. I knew her for many years, so we are pretty '''close'''.|C|ref='''2013''', {{lw|zh|董啟章}} ({{w|Dung Kai-cheung}}), {{lang|zh|《體育時期（劇場版）【上學期】》}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=F_HKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA124 page 124]}}\n#* {{zh-x|我 唔 想 我哋 只係 喺 呢{ni1} 段 時間{gaan3} friend\\'''F{f}r{}i{}end{1}''' 返，我 想 我哋 變返 以前 咁{gam2}，friend\\'''F{f}r{}i{}end{1}''' 到 乜 都 傾，平{ping4}時 大家 有 啲 咩 都 會 搵 大家 講。|I don't want us to just be '''close''' for this while. I want us to turn back into how we were before, when we were so '''close''' that we would chat about anything, when we would normally look for each other to talk if anything happens.|C|ref='''2015''', {{lang|zh|少少肥}} (pseudonym), {{lang|zh|《自修室‧學界嘅蘭桂坊》}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZLeaCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA243 page 243]}}\n#* {{zh-x|不過 始終 大家 都 係 細路，好 快 就 '''fr{}i{}end{1}''' 咗，我 個 人 好 易 相處，同 香港人、印度人 都 相處 到{dou3-2}，所以 其實 讀 咩 學校{haau6} 都 冇 問題。|But since everyone is a kid, we quickly became '''close'''. I easily get along with others, no matter if it's with Hong Kongers or Indians, so it doesn't matter which school I go to.|C|ref='''2016''', {{lw|zh|喬寶寶}}, ([[w:Gill Mohindepaul Singh|Q Bobo]]), {{lang|zh|《香港製造》}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NuzkDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA32 page 32]}}\n\n===Derived terms===\n{{col3|yue|friend子|friend底|friend過夾band|friend過打band}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:yue:ELHKC}}\n\n{{c|zh|People|Friendship}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|frend}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|frīend}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ang|noun form|head=frīend}}\n\n# {{inflection of|ang|frēond||dat|sg}}\n# {{inflection of|ang|frēond||nom|and|acc|p}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|es|en|friend}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr|frend}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|es|climbing}} [[cam]]\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|yol|noun}}\n\n# {{alt form|yol|vriene}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=VERSES IN ANSWER TO THE WEDDEEN O BALLYMORE|number=3|page=100|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Mye thee '''friend''' ne're waant welcome, nor straayart comfoort.|translation=May thy '''friend''' ne'er want welcome, nor the stranger comfort.}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Poole 1867|page=100}}"}}